<h1 style="text-align: center;"><em><strong><span style="color: #b23233;"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="269317" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/what-is-the-best-literary-film-adaptation-of-the-last-50-years/commitments-2/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/commitments.jpg" data-orig-size="800,450" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="commitments" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/commitments.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-269317" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/commitments.jpg" alt="" width="500" height="281" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/commitments.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/commitments-300x169.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/commitments-768x432.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/commitments-60x34.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/commitments-50x28.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px" />The Commitments</span></strong></em><br />
dir. Alan Parker, 1991</h1>
<h5></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Based on </strong>Roddy Doyle’s <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780679721741" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">The Commitments</a> </em>(1987)</h5>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Sub-genres: </strong> The Doyle-iverse • Great Nicknames • Cultural Exchanges • Great Moments in UK Up-Yours, Reverse-V Signs</h5>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>It’s the tunes for me. Because the minute I was asked to imagine “Dublin Soul,” I needed to hear it. The 1991 adaptation of Roddy Doyle’s novel follows a bunch of working class Irish heroes in somewhat-unlikely-thrall to Otis Redding. The movie’s own soul hinges on lengthy, stirring performances from the band. With special props to the mad frontman, Deco (Andrew Strong). –<em>Brittany Allen, Staff Writer</em></p>
