<h1 style="text-align: center;"><span style="color: #b23233;"><em><strong><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="269319" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/what-is-the-best-literary-film-adaptation-of-the-last-50-years/americanfiction/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/americanfiction.jpg" data-orig-size="800,450" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="americanfiction" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/americanfiction.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-269319" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/americanfiction.jpg" alt="" width="500" height="281" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/americanfiction.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/americanfiction-300x169.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/americanfiction-768x432.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/americanfiction-60x34.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/americanfiction-50x28.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px" />American Fiction</strong></em></span><br />
dir. Cord Jefferson, 2023</h1>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Based on </strong>Percival Everett’s <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781555975999" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Erasure</a></em> (2001)</h5>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Sub-genres: </strong> Satire On Satire • Academics vs. Hollywood • I&#8217;m Laughing But I&#8217;m Angry</h5>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Satire hinges on the specifics. The details need to be both plausible but still legible as comedy, otherwise the jokes will read as hamfisted, or won’t land at all. <em>Erasure </em>is full of those great details, from the book titles (<em>Chaldean Oracles</em> and <em>We&#8217;s Lives In Da Ghetto</em>) to the character names (Monk Ellison and Wiley Valdespino)—they just sound right. The escalation of the satire is excellent too, especially as Monk’s attempts to sabotage himself are repeatedly embraced by publishers and Hollywood. The film has to lose some of Everett’s great formal satire on page, of everything from academic articles to C.V.s, but more than makes up for it with excellent acting and direction. What makes Everett such an excellent satirist and Jefferson such an excellent director is that they give each character enough humanity and justification to never be fully right or wrong. In the end, who’s really in on the joke? –<em>James Folta, Staff Writer</em></p>
