dir. Alexander Payne, 1999</h1>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Based on </strong>Tom Perrotta’s <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780425167281" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Election</a></em> (1998)</h5>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Sub-genres: </strong> Not How I Remember High School • A Different Ending Than The Book • Hey Teacher, Leave Those Kids Alone</h5>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>I believe Alexander Payne to be a wizard of tone, and for proof I submit his sophomore film. <em>Election</em> is a ruthless, high-wire satire with its skeptical spectacles trained on authority itself. The Perrotta novel is a wisecracking romp; the film adaptation is transcendent. It’s all in the way the camera collects indignities—from Mr. McCallister’s beestung eye to Tracy’s frozen face in Social Studies. IMHO, this film ran so <em>Mean Girls</em>, another swell adaptation lampooning hierarchy, could trot. <em>–BA</em></p>
