<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Based on </strong>Daniel Clowes’s <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781560974277" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Ghost World </em></a>(1997)</h5>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Sub-genres:</strong> Why You Did That to Your Hair • Indie Sleaze • The Nerds Are Sad</h5>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>A special feat, I think, to take a graphic novel into live action airspace. Something could easily be lost in the move from 2D world into the tactile. We might go too cartoon-y, or not cartoon-y enough. Or the human actors could fail to live up to their illustrated avatars.</p>
<p>Thank heaven, then, for Terry Zwigoff’s <em>Ghost World</em>, which captures all the dour hijinks and cold freakery of its source text on an all-too-IRL plane. This film is perfectly calibrated and colorized. The saddies of Enid’s notebook all a little uncanny, as in any good comic, yet terribly human in their tragedies. (Seymour!!!) <em>–BA</em></p>
