dir. Park Chan-wook, 2016</h1>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Based on </strong>Sarah Waters’s <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781573229722" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Fingersmith</a></em> (2002)</h5>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Sub-genres: </strong>They Fixed It! • Metaphorical Molluscs • Wheels Within Wheels</h5>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Park Chan-wook manages to both honor and improve upon his source material in this out-of-the-box adaptation, which transposes the action from Victorian England to 1930s colonial Korea, and, honestly, fixes the third act. As an adaptation, it is a kind of wish fulfillment (no spoilers here, but you’ll know why if you’ve read the book), and is also bonkers gorgeous and, at times, quite terrifying. A feminist re-imagining of a feminist novel, complete with sinister octopus. <em>–ET</em></p>
