dir. Quentin Tarantino, 1997</h1>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Based on </strong>Elmore Leonard’s <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780062119827" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Rum Punch</a></em> (1992)</h5>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Sub-genres: </strong> Neo-Blaxploitation • Swapping And Reswapping Bags of Cash • Inventive Adaptations</h5>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Note to the engineers: there should be a sub-category in this bracket for adaptations that hinge on impeccable soundtracks—though honestly, such a sub-category would undersell <em>Jackie B</em>. My parents had <a href="https://music.apple.com/us/album/jackie-brown-music-from-the-miramax-motion-picture/316316847" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">this (perfect) CD</a> on in the car for most of 1998, but the real case for Jackie rests on casting. The elegantly sly Pam Grier, a long-time blaxploitation heroine, is reinvented in this lively caper as a con artist on a relatable mission: to retire. The rest of the cast is a winky murderer’s row of genre veterans, who all bring earnest cheek to their assignments. <em>–BA</em></p>
