</span></strong><strong>MATCHUP: </strong></h1>
<h1 style="text-align: center;"><strong><em>The Talented Mr. Ripley</em> (3) vs. <em>The Hunt for Red October</em> (14)</strong></h1>
<h1 style="text-align: center;"><strong><span style="color: #b23233;">******************************************</span></strong></h1>
<h1 style="text-align: center;"><span style="color: #b23233;"><em><strong><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="269502" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/what-is-the-best-literary-film-adaptation-of-the-last-50-years/ripley-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/ripley-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="800,450" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="ripley copy" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/ripley-copy.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-269502" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/ripley-copy.jpg" alt="" width="500" height="281" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/ripley-copy.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/ripley-copy-300x169.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/ripley-copy-768x432.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/ripley-copy-60x34.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/ripley-copy-50x28.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px" />The Talented Mr. Ripley</strong></em></span><br />
dir. Anthony Mingella, 1999</h1>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Based on </strong>Patricia Highsmith’s <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780393332148" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">The Talented Mr. Ripley</a></em> (1995)</h5>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Sub-genres: </strong> Beautiful People Doing Murders • Creating Text from Subtext • Boats are Dangerous</h5>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Matt Damon has never been more convincing than in his turn as Tom Ripley in Minghella’s unsettling and intoxicating adaptation of Highsmith’s complex thriller, but it’s Philip Seymour Hoffman who really steals the show, even against Jude Law, Gwyneth Paltrow, and Cate Blanchett as the invented but excellent Meredith. The warmth of the film—shot on location in Positano, Italy—only adds to its creeping, sexy menace. Is it better than the book? Not quite, but it makes an excellent companion piece. –<em>ET</em></p>
