<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Based on </strong>Thomas Pynchon’s <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780141180632" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Vineland</a></em> (1990)</h5>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Sub-genres: </strong> Viva La Revolución • Very Loose Adaptations • A Few Small Beers</h5>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>The most recent film to make our cut, and one of the most interesting adaptations from page to screen in years. <em>Vineland</em> is wildly different—set in a different decade and full of Pynchon&#8217;s typically batty rocket-flights of fancy—but PTA finds a thread of resonant plot and character that feels true to the source material and ripped from our very dark headlines. Great performances (Benicio del Toro, my king) and great editing makes <em>OBAA</em> the best of the recent films taking on This Moment Of Ours, more successful than the snotty <em>Eddington</em> or the loopy <em>Bugonia</em>. <em>—JF</em></p>
