</span></strong><strong>MATCHUP: </strong></h1>
<h1 style="text-align: center;"><strong><em>American Psycho</em> (5) vs. <em>Blade Runner</em> (12)</strong></h1>
<h1 style="text-align: center;"><strong><span style="color: #b23233;">******************************************</span></strong></h1>
<h1 style="text-align: center;"><span style="color: #b23233;"><em><strong><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="269537" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/what-is-the-best-literary-film-adaptation-of-the-last-50-years/americanpsycho-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/americanpsycho-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="800,450" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="americanpsycho copy" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/americanpsycho-copy.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-269537" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/americanpsycho-copy.jpg" alt="" width="500" height="281" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/americanpsycho-copy.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/americanpsycho-copy-300x169.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/americanpsycho-copy-768x432.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/americanpsycho-copy-60x34.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/americanpsycho-copy-50x28.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px" />American Psycho</strong></em></span><br />
dir. Mary Harron, 2000</h1>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Based on </strong>Bret Easton Ellis’s <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780679735779" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">American Psycho</a></em> (1991)</h5>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Sub-genres: </strong>Morning Routines • Exhibit A In The Media Literacy Crisis • Hot Takes on Fonts</h5>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Picking up from the book’s breathless lists of detail and brands, there’s so much texture on screen in <em>American Psycho. </em>It forms a thick crust of aesthetics that insulate the characters from self-reflection. Those vibe-y details are also easy to clip for a fan cam, and seem to distract many of today&#8217;s weirdest guys from being able to see the film’s satirical barbs. I would think it&#8217;s pretty clear what this movie is up to: Christian Bale is intensely creepy as a dead-eyed finance bro and director Mary Harron brutally dramatizes his descents into depravity. The book has a bit more shocking violence than we see in the film perhaps, but I don’t see how the point of <em>American </em><em>Psycho</em> could be more direct. I can’t fault the movie for the misreadings of the populace, but it certainly makes me feel some kind of way that Patrick Bateman has so many fans these days. –<em>JF</em></p>
