<h1 style="text-align: center;"><strong><em>The Shining</em> (4) vs. <em>The Green Knight</em> (13)</strong></h1>
<h1 style="text-align: center;"><strong><span style="color: #b23233;">******************************************</span></strong></h1>
<h1 style="text-align: center;"><span style="color: #b23233;"><em><strong><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="269541" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/what-is-the-best-literary-film-adaptation-of-the-last-50-years/theshining-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/theshining-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="800,450" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="theshining copy" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/theshining-copy.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-269541" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/theshining-copy.jpg" alt="" width="500" height="281" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/theshining-copy.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/theshining-copy-300x169.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/theshining-copy-768x432.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/theshining-copy-60x34.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/theshining-copy-50x28.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px" />The Shining</strong></em></span><br />
dir. Stanley Kubrick, 1980</h1>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Based on </strong>Stephen King’s <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780345806789" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">The Shining</a></em> (1977)</h5>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Sub-genres: </strong>Accurate Depictions of Writers • Famous Axes Of Cinema • Imagine The Trip Advisor Reviews</h5>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Here’s the thing: is this a great adaptation of the Stephen King novel <em>The Shining</em>? Not really. We all know how much King hates this version (so much so that he made his own! Which was worse, if more faithful!), but it’s like how <em>Throne of Blood</em> is probably the best cinematic <em>Macbeth</em>: Kubrick took the elements he liked, ditched the rest, and turned in one of the great horror films of all time. It doesn’t matter that we lose the psychological nuance of the novel or even that Jack Torrance is already well and truly haunted before he gets to the hotel—because Jack Nicholson’s performance gets at the core of the fear that’s animating King’s novel, just from a different direction. In King’s book, the hotel is evil; in Kubrick’s film, there’s plenty of human villainy to go around. Both are scary, both are exceptional. Perhaps that’s all a good adaptation needs to do. –<em>DB</em></p>
