<h1 style="text-align: center;"><span style="color: #b23233;"><em><strong><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="269553" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/what-is-the-best-literary-film-adaptation-of-the-last-50-years/carrie-6/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/carrie.jpg" data-orig-size="800,450" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="carrie" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/carrie.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-269553" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/carrie.jpg" alt="" width="500" height="281" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/carrie.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/carrie-300x169.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/carrie-768x432.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/carrie-60x34.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/carrie-50x28.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px" />Carrie</strong></em></span><br />
dir. Brian De Palma, 1976</h1>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Based on </strong>Stephen King’s <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781984898104" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Carrie</a></em> (1974)</h5>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Sub-genres: </strong>Bad Prom Dates • They Fixed It • The Stephen King Cinematic Universe</h5>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>A wildly influential film that spins high school revenge fantasy into a dizzyingly gory spectacle. The final sequence is pure American Giallo (complimentary): the bullies’ comeuppance is delivered with flying knives, a fire hose turned into a spitting cobra, and microphone electrocution. Sissy Spacek keeps the cast on track, and I think De Palma has a better handle on the story’s themes and anxieties than King does. De Palma gets the pain of youth on a more nuanced level, and smartly dials back the violent scale of the ending to put the focus closer to home. –<em>JF</em></p>
