dir. David Cronenberg, 1986</h1>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Based on </strong>George Langelaan’s &#8220;<a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780712352840" class="external" target="_blank">The Fly</a>&#8221; (1957)</h5>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Sub-genres: </strong> Bad Science • Goldblum’s Body Hair • Terrifying Rubber Monsters</h5>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>A grotesque masterpiece, and not for the faint of heart. Jeff Goldblum is perfect as the lanky mad scientist doing nude experiments in his warehouse lab, and his wide-eyed transformation into the horny, sugar-hungry man-fly underlines the weird anxieties that Cronenberg always brings to body horror. And I love Geena Davis in this—she has that B-movie scream queen skill of making each new freak-out seem distinct. Her character being a journalist is a good reminder that no matter how bad media seems to be doing these days, at least you’re not dating a source who’s turning into a fly-man. <em>–JF</em></p>
