<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://lithub.com/ted-chiang-on-arrival-the-boredom-of-moviemaking-and-the-princess-bride/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Ted Chiang on <em>Arrival</em>, the Boredom of Moviemaking, and<em> The Princess Bride</em></a> • <a href="https://lithub.com/why-arrival-looks-so-different-after-covid-19/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Why <em>Arrival</em> Looks So Different After COVID-19</a> • <a href="https://lithub.com/ted-chiang-on-superintelligence-and-its-discontents-in-j-d-beresfords-innovative-work-of-early-20th-century-science-fiction/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Ted Chiang on Superintelligence and Its Discontents in J.D. Beresford’s Innovative Work of Early 20th-Century Science Fiction</a></p>
<h1 style="text-align: center;"><strong>••••••••••vs••••••••••</strong></h1>
<h1 style="text-align: center;"><span style="color: #b23233;"><em><strong><a href="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/roger-copy.jpg"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="269559" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/what-is-the-best-literary-film-adaptation-of-the-last-50-years/roger-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/roger-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="800,450" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="roger copy" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/roger-copy.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-269559" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/roger-copy.jpg" alt="" width="500" height="281" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/roger-copy.jpg 800w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/roger-copy-300x169.jpg 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/roger-copy-768x432.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/roger-copy-60x34.jpg 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/roger-copy-50x28.jpg 50w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px" /></a>Who Framed Roger Rabbit?</strong></em></span><br />
dir. Robert Zemeckis, 1988</h1>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"></h5>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Based on </strong>Gary K. Wolf’s <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781512315011" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Who Censored Roger Rabbit?</a></em> (1981)</h5>
<h5 style="text-align: center;"><strong>Sub-genres: </strong> Bob Hoskins Resisting Silliness for as Long as Humanly Possible • Patty-Cake Erotica • Capitalism Is Bad</h5>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>I admit I have never read the source material for this one, so I can only speak to the film itself, which I loved before I had any point of reference for film noir (or, you know, evil conglomerates threatening to wipe out a people in service of &#8220;progress&#8221;). Bob Hoskins&#8217; Eddie Valiant is convincingly hard-boiled, even faced with the goofiest shit imaginable (and convincingly AH-OOO-GA for Jessica Rabbit, but who among us, etc., etc.), and while I won&#8217;t spoil the villain (other than capitalism), suffice it to say that &#8220;the dip&#8221; still haunts the nightmares of many an elder Millennial/young Gen-Xer.  –<em>JG</em></p>
